Here are some Instagram worthy shots of the living hell I’ve endured the last week… 🙃🧊❄️🤍 the hell we’ve all endured literally trapped on the mountain… and the blue skies and break in the storm we had on Sunday gave us all hope… but it was short-lived. The faces on my dogs in the last slide really sum it up well… anger and longing and desperation all mixed up with panic and fear. But at least we’ve had power and heat! 😑Yes. We’ve had the bare minimum and are all running out of food and can’t get out to get more because we still don’t have clear, plowed roads. To see a more accurate version of reality, well, my reality, check my SNOWMAGEDDON highlight for all the moods 🤣😩🤪🥶💀🖤🤍 or just enjoy these pretty shots of the snow and the now-frozen lake 🧊

#lakearrowhead #snowmageddon #winter #ilovelakearrowhead #frozen #californiamountains #snow  #snowedin #literallysnowedin #❄️ #ihavebeenaloneforaweekandiwanttocry #stuck #trapped

No. Immediately NO... day 8 

#lakearrowhead #blizzard #snow #snowpocalypse #snowmageddon #winter #help #winterwonderland #nope #weredonehere #snowday #makeitstop

The isolation, panic and terror, of being trapped alone in your home for 10+ days, running out of food and supplies, not seeing a single human for almost a week, was just the beginning of what many of us have gone through here in Lake Arrowhead and the surrounding mountain communities. 

Then came the gas leaks, explosions, collapsing rooftops, house fires buried in snow so deep the fire fighters couldn’t even get to them. Every bit of hope was followed by disappointment and more fear, anxiety and panic than the day before and we are not safe yet. 

As prepared as we are for our “normal” winter snow, nothing could have prepared us for this blizzard that hit so hard it quite literally blindsided us. 

We worked hard to maintain the snow with our shovels and small truck plows and snow blowers but we RELY on the front loading tractor plows to clear our streets and roads so we can get out. Instead we were left stranded, reaching out… running out of time and food and medicine and losing our mental health in the process. 

If it wasn’t for this great community of people sharing and helping, we would be in an even WORSE position than we currently are. And we STILL NEED HELP. 

We are not out of the woods yet, so to speak. 

This has been a nightmare, so surreal it only compares to a horror film, and it’s not over. We’re still up here asking for more help and we’re not getting what we need. 

It’s hard to see how devastating it truly has been when it’s also so incredibly beautiful. 🤍❄️

I’m not sure when we will recover from this mentally 😔 But we need help physically now to recover our safety. 🙏🤍

I just found this sweet little bird in my reel drafts that I never shared… and it feels like such a blur now. 

Seeing the sun shine and little creatures out and about were more than just normal signs of nature and wildlife, they were  signs of hope, signs of life after being alone for so long not seeing another human for almost 10 days, trapped by snow, worried about gas leaks and house explosions and house fires and roofs caving in and all the others trapped in their homes, hoping they were okay. 

Winter was brutal and I think it’s safe to say we might all have a little PTSD from the blizzard we experienced late February and March here on the mountain, even tho we all experienced it in different ways. 

There are still times I look out to the street or walkways and get flashbacks of snow piled so high it was beyond beautiful, it was terrifying.

Looking back I feel like I’m being  dramatic, like it wasn’t THAT BAD, but it was. I can only liken it to a horror film. 

My body is still holding onto the stress of it. My mind pushes away the overwhelming feelings and emotions that arise. It’s a bizarre experience that still doesn’t quite make sense. 

But it’s almost summer now, not quite warm enough to jump in the lake (for me anyway 😆) but we’re close - and yet every time I look at the lake the thought runs though my mind “water has memory” and wonder about its experience now having been Frozen. 

Trauma does funny things to us. 🤍

When I was packing to move last month I found my old @tiffanyandco key ring I haven’t used in years because I lost the ball… so I got crafty and fixed it! Here’s how I did it… 

1. Used a plastic craft pearl in a similar size to the sterling ball. NOTE: a wooden bead would probably work even better!

2. Grabbed a tiny drill bit from my stepdad’s garage that matched the size of the screw on the keychain. (Sorry I don’t know the actual size 😬 but I think it’s 1/8”)

3. Drilled out one side of the holes in the craft pearl just long enough to fit/touch the key ring

4. Screwed on the pearl! It actually grabbed the thread created from the drill and screwed on and off, no problem but I dabbed a bit of gorilla glue at the opposite end just to be safe. 

And… Voila! 💁🏼‍♀️ ready to use again!

I was super excited this actually worked! 😃🤩🥳 
Happy DIYing! 🩷 xoxo …love, Maegan 💋
